Sūri is the regular word in the Rigveda1 for the sacrificer, the
later Yajamāna — that is, the man who pays the priests for
performing the rite, and reaps the benefit of that service. The
Sūris are often coupled with the Maghavans,1 described as
heroes or warriors,2 and as related to the priests by their
patronage3 or as companions.4 1) i. 31, 7. 12; 48, 24; 54, 11; 73, 5.
8, 9; iii. 31, 14; v. 42, 4; 79, 6;
